	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I made a <a href="http://www.pineight.com/nes/#roulette" class="postlink">Russian roulette game for NES</a> as a Zapper tech demo, and <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=6567" class="postlink">people were disappointed</a> that it was text-based.
<br />
<br />But as for a game in the style of Infocom's text adventures, a pure text game wouldn't work because the 72-pin NES has no keyboard, as Shiru pointed out. You could have it use the Family Basic keyboard, but then you'd have to make the text in Japanese for the players to understand it. It took a tweak of the format to make it work on the NES; Memblers mentioned the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MacVenture" class="postlink">MacVenture</a> games developed by ICOM and Kemco. And does <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princess_Tomato_in_the_Salad_Kingdom" class="postlink">Princess Tomato in the Salad Kingdom</a> count?
<br />
<br />If you're looking for a genre to make in C for the NES, look no further than Koei's war sims. NovaYoshi has uncovered evidence in the games' strings that they use the C standard library.
<br />
<br />And cc65 isn't the only C compiler; there's also <a href="http://www.kdef.com/geek/vic/quetz.html" class="postlink">Quetzalcoatl</a>, which unlike cc65 is actually free software and suitable for use in commercial projects. There's <a href="http://osdk.defence-force.org/" class="postlink">OSDK</a>, a compiler based on LCC, but based on the description on the web site, it appears to be hardcoded for the Oric computers and difficult to adapt to other 6502 machines.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


